Create Target Variable: Goal Superiority

For team-level data, we are predicting âgoal superiority,â aka whether (1) or not (0) a team achieved the majority of goals against a specific opposing team in the season.

To create a âgoal superiorityâ variable, we compare the variables goalsFor and goalsAgainst (the scoreboard score; the number of times the puck actually crossed the goal line into the opponentâs net during a game) and xGoalsFor and xGoalsAgainst (a statistical estimate of how many goals a team should have scored based on the quality of their scoring chances) to create this binary classification.

df <- df |>
  filter(situation == "all") |>
  mutate(
    result = case_when(
      goalsFor > goalsAgainst ~ 1,
      goalsFor < goalsAgainst ~ 0,
      goalsFor == goalsAgainst ~ 0
    ),
    xresult = case_when(
      xGoalsFor > xGoalsAgainst ~ 1,
      xGoalsFor < xGoalsAgainst ~ 0,
      xGoalsFor == xGoalsAgainst ~ 0
    )
  ) |>
  filter(result != "OT")

Select Predictors

We should choose an initial set of predictors that we think are most related to scoring, which would be variables related to game context, offensive and defensive performance,

Here are a few definitions for variables where the meaning isnât obvious:

  • highDangerxGoalsFor & highDangerxGoalsAgainst: Goals from high danger shots

  • shotAttemptsFor: Shot attempts. Includes shots on goal, missed shots, and blocked shot attempts

  • corsiPercentage: Share of total shot attempts (measures a playerâs ability to control the puck and create offensive opportunities)

  • fenwickPercentage: measures a teamâs unblocked shot attempts relative to their opponentâs

  • dZoneGiveawaysFor: Giveaways in the teamâs defensive zone. Giveaways shows how much a player has the puck and riskiness.

  • xGoalsFromxReboundsOfShotsFor: Expected Goals from Expected Rebounds of playerâs shots. Even if a shot does not actually generate a rebound, if itâs a shot that is likely to generate a rebound the player is credited with xGoalsFromxRebounds

df <- df |> dplyr::select(xresult, playerTeam, opposingTeam, home_or_away, highDangerxGoalsFor, shotAttemptsFor, highDangerxGoalsAgainst, corsiPercentage, fenwickPercentage, dZoneGiveawaysFor, xGoalsFromxReboundsOfShotsFor)

logreg.vars.poly <- glm(xresult ~ shotAttemptsFor + poly(highDangerxGoalsAgainst, 2) + poly(highDangerxGoalsFor, 2) + poly(xGoalsFromxReboundsOfShotsFor, 2) + fenwickPercentage + playerTeam + opposingTeam + home_or_away, family = binomial, data = df)

Outliers

leverage <- hatvalues(logreg.vars)
cd <- cooks.distance(logreg.vars)
car::infIndexPlot(logreg.vars)

.03 is a common but conservative threshold for identifying points of possible interest due to high leverage (hat values). Cooks distance > 1 focuses on measuring the influence of points on the model

Point 1781 is the only point that, relative to other observations, has high leverage and high influence. But no points, including 1781, come close the Cookâs Distance Threshold > 1, so no outliers need to be removed.

Model Selection

To compare final models, we do the following:

  1. Fit a model using the above finalized list of predictors on all of the data

  2. Select a classification probability threshold based on whichever threshold produces the highest classification rate.

  3. Compute the ROC AUC across a range of thresholds

  4. Compare performance metrics:

    1. Obtain final accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity based on a 70/30 test train split for logreg, lda/qda, and knn.

    2. Obtain final accuracy based on k-fold 10 for logreg and lda/qda models.

Threshold Tuning

  • True positive: predicted majority wins & actual majority wins
  • True negatives: predicted majority loss & actual majority losses
  • False positives: predicted majority wins & actual majority losses
probs <- predict(logreg, type = "response")
threshold <- seq(0, 1, .01)

tpr <- tnr <- fpr <- class.rate <- err.rate <- rep(0, length(threshold))

for (i in seq_along(threshold)) {
  yhat <- rep(NA_character_, nrow(df))
  yhat <- ifelse(probs >= threshold[[i]], 1, 0)

  class.rate[i] <- mean(yhat == df$xresult)
  err.rate[i] <- 1 - class.rate[i]

  tpr[[i]] <- sum((yhat == 1) & (df$xresult == 1)) / sum(df$xresult == 1)
  tnr[[i]] <- sum((yhat == 0) & (df$xresult == 0)) / sum(df$xresult == 0)
  fpr[[i]] <- sum((yhat == 1) & (df$xresult == 0)) / sum(df$xresult == 0)
}

ggplot(
  tibble(threshold, class.rate),
  aes(threshold, class.rate)
) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = threshold[which.max(class.rate)], color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Threshold Tuning for Max Class Rate: LogReg") +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 20),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 15),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 14),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 12)
  )

CV

L <- function(Y, p) {
  mean(1 * (Y == 1 & p <= best_threshold) | (1 * (Y == 0 & p > best_threshold)),
    na.rm = TRUE
  )
}

Quadratic Discriminant Analysis

qda.fit <- qda(xresult ~ fenwickPercentage + highDangerxGoalsFor +

Threshold Tuning

probs <- predict(qda.fit)$posterior[, 2]
threshold <- seq(0, 1, .01)

tpr <- tnr <- fpr <- class.rate <- err.rate <- rep(0, length(threshold))

for (i in seq_along(threshold)) {
  yhat <- rep(NA_character_, nrow(df))
  yhat <- ifelse(probs >= threshold[[i]], 1, 0)

  class.rate[i] <- mean(yhat == df$xresult)
  err.rate[i] <- 1 - class.rate[i]

  tpr[[i]] <- sum((yhat == 1) & (df$xresult == 1)) / sum(df$xresult == 1)
  tnr[[i]] <- sum((yhat == 0) & (df$xresult == 0)) / sum(df$xresult == 0)
  fpr[[i]] <- sum((yhat == 1) & (df$xresult == 0)) / sum(df$xresult == 0)
}

ggplot(
  tibble(threshold, class.rate),
  aes(threshold, class.rate)
) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = threshold[which.max(class.rate)], color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Threshold Tuning for Max Class Rate: QDA") +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 20),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 15),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 14),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 12)
  )
best_threshold <- threshold[which.max(class.rate)]
best_threshold
[1] 0.5

KNN

Best K & Test/Train Split

X <- c("fenwickPercentage", "highDangerxGoalsFor", "highDangerxGoalsAgainst", "xGoalsFromxReboundsOfShotsFor", "shotAttemptsFor", "home_or_away")

train$home_or_away <- as.numeric(as.factor(train$home_or_away))
test$home_or_away <- as.numeric(as.factor(test$home_or_away))


x_train <- train[, X]
x_test <- test[, X]
y_train <- train$xresult
y_test <- test$xresult

knn_rate <- rep(0, 60)

for (k in 1:60) {
  set.seed(123)
  knn_fit <- knn(x_train, x_test, y_train, k)
  knn_rate[k] <- mean(knn_fit == y_test)
}

ggplot(
  tibble(k = seq(1, 60), `Correct Classification Rate` = knn_rate),
  aes(k, `Correct Classification Rate`)
) +
  geom_point()
which.max(knn_rate)
[1] 42
knn_fit <- knn(x_train, x_test, y_train, 42)
